Inscription, partially obscured: 
"... the gift of My Dear Mother to E[...] Shottesbrook[e] [...] this incomparable was My Grandmother's [...] The Oak [...] the pious accomplished [...] of Shottesbrook[e] House.  She the eldest of the five co-heiress of the very pious learned John Finch Esq. of Fien[e]s Court near Maidenhead.  [Signed][?] 1755."

comment.author: 70213421@N02
comment.text: I can't read the signature, but I think the inscription is referring to Elizabeth (or Eliza) Finch, who was the eldest of the five daughters of John Finch Esq., of Fienes or Feens Manor or Court, in White Waltham. White Waltham encompasses the Shottesbrooke House and Fienes or Feens Manor, in Berkshire, England, and is near Maidenhead. Eliza married Francis Cherry, of Shottesbrooke House, and lived there with him. As her father had had no male heirs, she and and her sisters inherited the near-bye Fienes Manor. This inscription seems to be written by a grand-child of Elizabeth Finch (or Cherry). Cf. this geneaology website and Remarks and Collections of Thomas Hearne. (Francis Cherry was the neighbor and patron of Thomas Hearne, of White Waltham, a historian and librarian at the Bodleian Library).

comment.text: Bookplate of Henry J.B. Clements (1869-1940) pasted over English ms. note in pencil on front pastedown. According to this article at the Victoria and Albert Museum website, Clements was an "acknowledged expert in the field of bindings displaying armorial and ownership devices." He also collected such bindings and bequeathed his collection to the V&A in 1940. Now the National Art Library Collection of Armorial Bindings, it "represents the most comprehensive collection of its kind. It allows perhaps more than three quarters of all British armorial ownership stamps to be identified. Much work was done by Clements himself on identifying the stamps and correcting the inaccuracies in the then standard textbook by Cyril Davenport ... Along with the bindings he bequeathed his copious notes, an annotated copy of Davenport and the very fine bookcases in which the collection is housed in the National Art Library" (ibid.). Established heading: Clements, Henry J. B. (Henry John Beresford), 1869-1940

Guillaume Libri (1803-1869), born Guglielmo Libri, conte Carrucci della Somaia, was an Italian mathematician and notorious book thief. Forced to flee Italy for his political views, he became a French citizen and in 1841 was appointed secretary of the Commission du Catalogue général des manuscrits des bibliothèques publiques de France. In 1848 he escaped to England with his loot, one step ahead of the police, and in 1851 was convicted of theft in absentia in France and sentenced to 10 years imprisonment. comment.text:
Cut-out pasted onto the flyleaf of the book.  A printer's mark used by the Verdussen family of printers in Antwerp (active 1593- 1857) (See: Marques typographique des pays-bas, I, Anvers, Famille Verdussen, no. 26).  Possibly specifically associated with Jan Baptiste Verdussen II (1659-1759).  A Christie's auction record alludes to a "bookplate" with motto "Virtus pietas homini tutissima" on both pastedowns associated with him, which may or may not be a similar cut out piece, and the engraving and paper appear to date from around the 17th century.  

The motto roughly translates as "piety is the most secure virtue for men."  The image of the stork feeding its young was a popular emblem of familial piety, demonstrating the way in which the pious bird teaches its young to hunt and devour the snake, symbolizing the devil.  Other printers are known to have used a similar device (see: Guy de Terverent. Attributes et Symbols dans l'arte profane. Geneva: Librarie Droz, 1997. p. 125.)

That is, the words "ET BEAUVILLAIN? toujours il vous aime" that appear on the bookplate are a direct quote from a Victor Hugo play referring to, as far as I can determine, a fictional character by the name of Beauvillain.  I wonder if someone just saw the name and, not knowing that it is a quote from Hugo, assumed that it belonged to the library of someone named Beauvillain?  Of course it would be awesome if there did turn out to be a real life bookowner named Beauvillain who used the Hugo quote because it referred to him.
